stanford synchrotron radiation lightsource science summary february 2012 structural basis of photoactivation of a bacterial dna binding protein stanford synchrotron radiation lightsource an office of science user facility quick facts 1 nobel prize winner 3 gev spear3 accelerator 30 experimental stations 300 institutions participating over 2000 scientists science at ssrl science highlights scientific techniques spear3 parameters publications beam lines contact us 2575 sand hill road menlo park ca 94025 usa 650 926 4000 map contact us home structural basis of photoactivation of a bacterial dna binding protein ssrl science summary 2012 biological sciences light oxygen voltage lov domain macromolecular crystallography bl9 1 fig 1 the dark state crystal structure of el222 with lov domain in blue hth domain in gold and the j helix connecting the two in bronze reveals extensive lov hth interactions predicted to inhibit hth dna binding activity organisms ability to sense and respond to light could be extraordinarily useful in biotechnology if researchers can learn to understand the processes that enable light stimulation recently a team of researchers from the university of california irvine university of california santa cruz and university of texas took a significant step toward understanding these processes in their study of one particular type of light sensing domain termed the light oxygen voltage lov domain found in plants animals and bacteria the lov domain controls a wide variety of biological processes to better understand how light stimulation of the lov domain activates so many different effector domains and whether the various activation mechanisms are similar the team measured diffraction data at ssrl beam line 9 1 on el222 a bacterial dna binding protein that consists of a light sensing domain coupled to a dna binding domain with these data the team was able to solve the structure of the el222 protein revealing that the main interaction between the two domains occurs at the interface between the beta sheet of the lov domain in blue in figure 1 and helix 4a of the dna binding domain this interaction is postulated to minimize the dna binding domain's activity in the dark this is the first solved structure of a naturally occurring lov sensor effector pair as understanding the molecular mechanism of how organisms use lov domains might enable engineered light induced control of pathways this work has implications for the emerging field of optogenetics which uses light controlled proteins to modulate cell activity in addition light based therapy might one day supplement or replace pills in the treatment of a variety of disorders publication ai nash r mcnulty me shillito te swartz ra bogomolni h luecke kh gardner structural basis of photosensitivity in a bacterial light oxygen voltage helix turn helix lov hth dna binding protein pnas 108 9449 9454 2011 related links full scientific highlight contacts hartmut luecke login to post comments share printer friendly version post to twitter send to friend send to friend ssrl is supported by the department of energy office of basic energy sciences the ssrl structural molecular biology program is supported by the department of energy office of biological and environmental research and by the national institutes of health national center for research resources biomedical technology program and the national institute of general medical sciences the stanford synchrotron radiation lightsource is a directorate of slac national accelerator laboratory which is operated by stanford university for the department of energy stay connected twitter flickr youtube this site rss other news sources slac today ssrl headlines symmetry magazine lightsources org interactions org ilc newsline spires slac national accelerator laboratory slac national accelerator laboratory menlo park ca operated by stanford university for the us department of energy office of science content owner cathy knotts privacy notice